    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Defining Our Values</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Iris Kaufman letter replying to David Brooks's Jan 14 column says as an American she is not confused about meanings of equality and freedom</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''The American Way of Equality'' (column, Jan. 14), David Brooks says: ''When Americans use the word 'equality,' they really mean 'fair opportunity.' When Americans use the word 'freedom,' they really mean 'opportunity.' ''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''The American Way of Equality'' (column, Jan. 14), David Brooks says: ''When Americans use the word 'equality,' they really mean 'fair opportunity.' When Americans use the word 'freedom,' they really mean 'opportunity.' ''</p>
        <p>That's what one conservative columnist may think we believe. But when this American uses the word ''equality,'' I mean ''equal opportunity.'' When I use the word ''freedom,'' I'm referring to the rights guaranteed to Americans by our Constitution, including the Bill of Rights.</p>
        <p>Freedom is precious. No American should be confused about it.</p>
        <p>Iris Kaufman  Swampscott, Mass., Jan. 14, 2007</p>
      </block>
